---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const valueCopy = `var a = 10;
var b = a;

b = 99;

Console.WriteLine(a); // 10
Console.WriteLine(b); // 99`;

const referenceCopy = `var first = new Person("Ada");
var second = first;

second.Name = "Grace";

Console.WriteLine(first.Name);  // Grace
Console.WriteLine(second.Name); // Grace

class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }

    public Person(string name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}`;

const nullableWarning = `string name = null; // warning with nullable reference types enabled

Console.WriteLine(name.Length); // possible crash at runtime`;

const nullableIntent = `string? maybeName = FindName();

if (maybeName is not null)
{
    Console.WriteLine(maybeName.Length);
}`;

---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 2 · C# value types, reference types, and null"
  heading="Value, reference, and the danger of <code>null</code>"
  lede="Today’s win: predict whether assignment copies the value itself or copies a reference to the same object."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="The first-principles model">
    <Callout>
      A variable slot either directly contains a small value, or it contains a reference that points to an object somewhere else.
    </Callout>
    <p>
      In C#, types such as <code>int</code>, <code>bool</code>, <code>decimal</code>, <code>DateTime</code>, and most <code>struct</code>s are value types. Classes, strings, arrays, lists, and most objects you create with <code>new SomeClass(...)</code> are reference types.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Value types copy the value">
    <p>When you assign an <code>int</code> to another variable, you get another <code>int</code> value. Changing one variable does not change the other.</p>
    <Code code={valueCopy} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Reference types copy the reference">
    <p>When you assign a class instance to another variable, you usually copy the reference. Both variables can point at the same object.</p>
    <Code code={referenceCopy} lang="csharp" />
    <p><code>first</code> and <code>second</code> are separate variable slots, but the copied reference points to the same <code>Person</code> object.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Where <code>null</code> enters">
    <p>
      A reference variable can sometimes point to nothing. That nothing is <code>null</code>. If you access a member through <code>null</code>, your program can throw a <code>NullReferenceException</code>.
    </p>
    <Code code={nullableWarning} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Modern C# wants you to state uncertainty">
    <p>
      With nullable reference types enabled, <code>string</code> means “I expect a real string”, while <code>string?</code> means “this might be missing.” The compiler then pushes you to check before using it.
    </p>
    <Code code={nullableIntent} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Retrieval checkpoint" variant="warning">
    <p>Answer without running code:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Why does the first example print <code>10</code> and <code>99</code>?</li>
      <li>Why does changing <code>second.Name</code> also affect <code>first.Name</code>?</li>
      <li>What practical promise does <code>string</code> make that <code>string?</code> does not?</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>
</SessionPage>
